column9: no, the build failed for another reason
column10: What happened in this case is that I provided a pull request with a single commit that fixed some Erlang file and then, somebody else, from the Erlang/OTP team, went ahead and added an extra, erroneous commit to this PR whose intention was to update the documentation.  As you can see here (https://travis-ci.org/erlang/otp/builds/553211512), most of the builds passed except from the last one which builds the documentation.
column11: You can see the discussion on the relevant PR (https://github.com/erlang/otp/pull/2309).

column10: The "real" cause of the failure was that in "poisoned gettext" scenarios the code using standard error texts from called programs got unexpected garbage and so failed. I am not sure this is exposed in the logs directly, but at least the git project has a link in the end of logs, under "ci/print-test-failures.sh", to detail the failure and let download the relevant files from test workspace.
